Description: This PHP example creates a new account link payload which includes scope, redirect URL, and reference ID. Also, this module creates a message and decodes user authorization.
This PHP example demonstrates how to test payload method chaining. The application creates a new QR code payload.
This Python example uses the appropriate package to perform simulated annealing. The simulation is run in threads using the ThreadPoolExecutor module.
This Python example performs transform method testing. This application checks if the implementation returns the most common value in the chain, and if value discarding works as intended.
This Python example demonstrates how to perform diagnostics related to chain overlapping, chain disconnections, invalid nodes, and missing edges.
This Python example demonstrates how to use the System SDK to embed D-Wave chain breaks. This performs several matrix method tests.
This Python example demonstrates how to perform calls to get database path, start a clean connection, close the memory connection, and manipulate the database.
This example demonstrates how to list XEDI users in TypeScript. This test application calls the /1/users endpoint and returns a JSON positive response.
TypeScript example that demonstrates how to retrieve a user by providing its ID and calling the /1/users endpoint. Positive responses are JSON formatted.
This TypeScript example demonstrates how to restore an Axios instance by providing its ID. This returns a JSON response with the results.
This demonstrates how to delete an Axios instance by providing its ID. Positive responses are JSON formatted.
This TypeScript example demonstrates how to create an Axios instance connected to XEDI. Positive responses are JSON formatted.
This TypeScript example demonstrates how to test a XEDI logout implementation. This removes Tokens and stored contexts, asynchronously.
This TypeScript example demonstrates how to test a login implementation. The application checks that user details and Tokens are stored properly.
PHP example that demonstrates how to send emails using the SendGrid-XEDI integration. This requires a SendGrid API Key.
The Contacts+ Exchanging an Authorization Code JavaScript Sample Code demonstrates how to use a client ID, client secret, redirect URI, scope, and a user agent to access an exchange auth code.
The Contacts+ Exchanging an Authorization Code C# Sample Code demonstrates how to use the Contacts API. It contains a client ID and a client secret to access the exchange auth code.

The Contacts+ Exchanging an Authorization Code Java Sample Code demonstrates how to access the Contacts API that contains a client ID and a client secret. The API response body shows the client's OAuth code.
The Contacts+ Exchanging an Authorization Code Clojure Sample Code provides a core example. The sample includes how to use a client ID, a client secret, and a redirect URI.
The Contacts+ Exchanging an Authorization Code Curl Sample Code demonstrates how to redirect to a supplied redirect_uri, once the user has authorized an app.
This Python example uses the CardService module to complete a card charge. This sends card information as a JSON payload to the SeerBit servers, handles the response, and prints the result.
Python example that demonstrates how to validate one time passwords using the CardService module. This takes private and public keys, authenticates using a token, and prints the result.
This Python example uses the CardService module to initiate card tokenization. This test application sends detailed card information as a JSON payload, and prints the result.
This example demonstrates how to initiate a card payment refund in Python. This module takes credit card details, stops the refund process, and outputs a JSON response.
This Python example performs card pre-auth using a Token string. This takes credit card details, and outputs a JSON response.
